- This specification indicates a new IPv6-Compression-Protocol field
- value for [SCHC] (see Section 5), and enables to transport a Uniform
- Resource Identifier (URI) [RFC3986] of the set of rules in the
- optional data.  The default format for the set of rules is YANG using
- the "Data Model for SCHC" [SCHC_DATA_MODEL] encoded in JSON as
- specified in [RFC7951].  The size of the URL is computed based on the
- Length of the option as Length-4.  If the encoding is asymetrical,
- the initiator of the session is considered downstream, playing the
- role of the device in an LPWAN network.
+ This specification indicates a new IPv6-Compression-Protocol field
+ value for [SCHC] (see Section 5), and enables to transport a Uniform
+ Resource Identifier (URI) [RFC3986] of the Set of Rules in the
+ optional data.  Signaling the URI at session setup is how the shared
+ Context is fetched on demand, as described for PPP in the SCHC
+ Architecture [I-D.ietf-schc-architecture].  The default format for the
+ Set of Rules is YANG using the "YANG Data Model for SCHC" [RFC9363]
+ encoded in JSON as specified in [RFC7951].  The size of the URI is
+ computed based on the Length of the option as Length-4.  If the Rules
+ are asymmetric, the SCHC Instance that initiates the PPP session plays
+ the role of the Device defined in [SCHC], following the role
+ convention of the SCHC Architecture; the peer Instance plays the
+ complementary (network-side) role.


## Section 4 - Profiling SCHC for high speed links
## Section 4.1 - Mapping the SCHC Architecture

- This specification leverages SCHC between an end point that is an IP
- Host and possibly a serial DTE (Data Terminal Equipment), and another
- that is an IP Node (either another IP Host or a Router) and possibly
- a serial DCE (Data Control Equipment), or a more modern physical or
- emulated endpoint, e.g., Ethernet devices that echange IP packets
- over PPPoE.
-
- Both endpoints MUST support the function of SCHC Compressor/
- Decompressor (C/D) as shown in Figure 2.
+ This specification leverages SCHC between a SCHC Endpoint hosted on an
+ IP Host and possibly a serial DTE (Data Terminal Equipment), and
+ another SCHC Endpoint hosted on an IP Node (either another IP Host or a
+ Router) and possibly a serial DCE (Data Control Equipment), or on a
+ more modern physical or emulated node, e.g., Ethernet devices that
+ exchange IP packets over PPPoE.  Each Endpoint associates one SCHC
+ Instance with the PPP connection; the PPP connection itself serves as
+ the Discriminator, and PPP demultiplexing acts as the Dispatcher that
+ routes SCHC Datagrams to that Instance.
+
+ The Instance on each Endpoint MUST support the SCHC Compression/
+ Decompression (C/D) function as shown in Figure 2.

# (Figure 2 unchanged.)

- The SCHC Fragmenter/Reassembler (F/R) is generally not needed,
- because the maximum transmission unit (MTU) is expected to be large
- enough and SCHC only reduces the frame size vs. native IP.  But it
- may be used to obtain a small protocol-independant frame size for the
- compressed packets, possibly way smaller than MTU.
+ The SCHC Fragmentation/Reassembly (F/R) function is generally not
+ needed, because the maximum transmission unit (MTU) is expected to be
+ large enough and SCHC only reduces the frame size vs. native IP.  But
+ it may be used to obtain a small protocol-independent frame size for
+ the SCHC Datagrams, possibly way smaller than MTU.

- A context may be generated for a particular upper layer application,
- such as a control loop using an industrial automation protocol, to
- protect the particular flow with a DetNet service.  The context can
- be asymetric, e.g., when connecting a primary and a secondary
- endpoints, a client and a server, or a programmable logic controller
- with a sensor or an actuator.
+ A Context may be generated for a particular upper layer application,
+ such as a control loop using an industrial automation protocol, to
+ protect the particular flow with a DetNet service.  The Context may
+ contain asymmetric Rules, in which case the two Instances play
+ distinct roles, e.g., when connecting a primary and a secondary
+ Endpoint, a client and a server, or a programmable logic controller
+ with a sensor or an actuator.


